    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Between the Conventions, Lieberman Is Topic A</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Michael Burke letter on Aug 9 article suggests Sen Joseph I Lieberman's observance of Jewish Sabbath will continue to resonate well with voters</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Gore and Lieberman Make Tolerance the Centerpiece'' (front page, Aug. 9):</p>
        <p>Some have wasted no time debating whether the country can handle a vice president who doesn't work on the Jewish Sabbath, from sundown Friday to sundown Saturday.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Gore and Lieberman Make Tolerance the Centerpiece'' (front page, Aug. 9):</p>
        <p>Some have wasted no time debating whether the country can handle a vice president who doesn't work on the Jewish Sabbath, from sundown Friday to sundown Saturday.</p>
        <p>But given the results of a poll showing that Vice President Al Gore closed the gap with Gov. George W. Bush after choosing Joseph I. Lieberman as his running mate, the American people apparently don't think that there is a problem.</p>
        <p>My guess is that Senator Lieberman's observance of the Sabbath will continue to resonate well with voters. First, it's a demonstration of faith in this day and age of all-talk, no-action religion.</p>
        <p>But more important, it shows that Mr. Lieberman is a politician who puts something above politics. Especially since the evolution of the 24-hour news cycle, voters have grown so weary and distrustful of 24/7 politics that a 24/6 candidate seems like a breath of fresh air.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL BURKE  Chicago, Aug. 9, 2000</p>
      </block>
